    "body": "I'm trying to understand how to port some Numpy code in Cython.\r\nBelow you can see a `run` function, which uses a loop to assign values to a slice of a Numpy array, and a `run2` variation that would use a more compact (and coincidentally faster) notation, and a `run3a/b` variation which does not work.\r\n\r\n```\r\nimport numpy as np\r\ncimport numpy as cnp\r\n\r\ncdef double nan = np.nan\r\nlog = np.log\r\n\r\ncdef double[:,:] A = np.full([10, 10000], nan, dtype=np.double)\r\ncdef double[:,:] B = np.full([10, 10000], nan, dtype=np.double)\r\n\r\n\r\ncpdef run():\r\n    cdef int t = 0\r\n    cdef int j\r\n    cdef double a = 800.\r\n    for j in range(10000):\r\n        A[t,j] = a\r\n        B[t,j] = j*(log((A[t,j]) / 2.))\r\n    return np.mean(B[t])\r\n\r\n\r\ncpdef run2():\r\n    cdef int t = 0\r\n    cdef double[:] J = np.arange(10000, dtype=np.double)\r\n    cdef cnp.ndarray a = np.array(800, dtype=np.double)\r\n    A[t] = a\r\n    cdef double[:] ret\r\n    ret = np.multiply(J, (log(((np.divide(A[t], 2.))))))\r\n    B[t] = ret\r\n    return np.mean(B[t])\r\n\r\n\r\ncpdef run3a():\r\n    cdef int t = 0\r\n    cdef double[:] J = np.arange(10000, dtype=np.double)\r\n    cdef cnp.ndarray a = np.array(800, dtype=np.double)\r\n    A[t] = a\r\n    B[t] = np.multiply(J, (log(((np.divide(A[t], 2.))))))  # TypeError: only size-1 arrays can be converted to Python scalars\r\n    return np.mean(B[t])\r\n\r\n\r\ncpdef run3b():\r\n    cdef int t = 0\r\n    cdef double[:] J = np.arange(10000, dtype=np.double)\r\n    cdef cnp.ndarray a = np.array(800, dtype=np.double)\r\n    A[t] = a\r\n    cdef double[:] ret\r\n    ret = J*log(A[t] / 2.) # Invalid operand types for '/' (double[:]; double)\r\n    B[t] = ret\r\n    return np.mean(B[t])\r\n```\r\n\r\nCould somebody explain why `run3a` gives me a `TypeError: only size-1 arrays can be converted to Python scalars` exception, and `run3b` gives me a `Invalid operand types for '/' (double[:]; double)` compilation error?  Ideally I would like to write\r\n```\r\nB[t] = J*log(A[t] / 2.)\r\n```\r\nwhich seems to be valid Numpy code. Why doesn't this work?\r\nAlso why `run2` is faster than `run`? (But that's probably because I'm not use pure C arrays and not disabling any checking.)\r\n\r\nI run the code above (assuming it's stored in the file `cython_test.py`) with\r\n```\r\nimport pyximport\r\nimport numpy as np\r\npyximport.install(setup_args={\"include_dirs\": np.get_include()},\r\n                  reload_support=True)\r\nimport timeit\r\nimport cython_test as ct\r\nprint(ct.run())\r\nprint(timeit.timeit('ct.run()', number=100, globals=globals()))\r\n#print(ct.run2())\r\n#print(timeit.timeit('ct.run2()', number=100, globals=globals()))\r\n#print(ct.run3a())\r\n#print(timeit.timeit('ct.run3a()', number=100, globals=globals()))\r\n#print(ct.run3b())\r\n#print(timeit.timeit('ct.run3b()', number=100, globals=globals()))\r\n```\r\n\r\n\r\nThanks a lot",
